				<BR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<HR>
JYolla wrote:<BR>
<DIV>Good message:</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>After my SH experience, I&nbsp;agree all&nbsp;event loot should be&nbsp;NO DROP. And this is coming from a non-65er.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>Making at least the most attractive loot&nbsp;NO DROP&nbsp;will automatically turn rolls into an NGB situation and </DIV>
<DIV>prevent twikage. However, a little more thought should be placed in the distribution of loot as well. GMs (should) have tools to determine the server population breakdown. If there are a large percentage of rangers, pallies, clerics, or any other class, tune loot accordingly. Same loot gets old fast and agree on the COF, Fungus comment.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>BTW, still yet to see a non-raid, non-event&nbsp;MGB.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV><BR>
<HR>
<BR></BLOCKQUOTE>
<DIV></DIV>
<P>Actually, the fix for that would be to have the GM's distribute loot after the event, and give them a little bit of discretion on which items are being handed out. Its usually a good idea that the items dropping for an event, match the population of the event, not the server as a whole. When an event is designed, give the GM a&nbsp;"custom kit" of items, of which they&nbsp;can award a certain number, but don't force them to choose until the&nbsp;event is assembled.&nbsp; </P>
<P>NO DROP doesn't completely solve the NBG issue either. Let me give this example, I happen to think it would be acceptable if a robe happened to drop that was NO DROP and "similar" in stats to the tradeable robe I'm currently wearing, I would consider rolling on the NO DROP robe, then selling my existing one so I can chase an upgrade in a different slot (or start saving money for OoW spells <img src='/i/smilies/16x16_smiley-wink.gif' width=16 height=16 border=0> ). You will never completely get away from this issue, but it would be nice if casters weren't winning SoD's. </P>
<P>The GM who was on last night did give one warning, and I'll loosely paraphrase: No two GMs are alike, and they all have slightly different theories and preferences as to how loot should be distributed.&nbsp; Personally, I like the idea of seeing a few more NO DROP items, then allowing rolls for people who <EM>can</EM> equip an item. To try and analyze it beyond that adds way too much time to the process. </P>
				
